column4:
For example: ambiguities in complicated sentences (commonly laid at the door of the "Oxford comma", and sometimes the cause of lawsuits)
can be considered syntax errors;
misunderstandings between parties can be considered failures of requirements elicitation, and can be discovered prior to contract signing
using methodologies like behaviour-driven development and unit testing;
under-specification can be mechanically detected by methods borrowed from functional programming such as type checking and totality analysis; and
more mundanely, version control and structured data embedded in documents provide basic levels of machine-readability lacking today.

As any practitioner of Test-Driven Development knows, a comprehensive test suite is worth its weight in gold
because it allows the software to change while preserving confidence that the changes didn't break anything;
and if they did break something the tests quickly point to what needs to be fixed.

column8:
function rule (…, party, attribute, value, …) {
   if (! predicate(party[attribute]) { return }
}

function rule (…, party, attribute, …) {
   if (! party.attribute) { return }
}

function rule (…, party, attribute, attributeParameters, …) {
   if (! party.attribute( attributeParameters )) { return }
}
